Unit complete. This iteration executed the **CR-6 + CR-7 research pair** for the Round 00 research gate.

**CR-6 — Tailings residual grades** (`research/r00-tailings-grades.md`): The literature confirms real, structural fine-particle and mica-hosted lithium losses in conventional spodumene flotation (e.g. ~93% of Li hosted in spodumene with the rest largely unrecoverable; ~8% Li lost to DMS tailings; fines <30 μm typically deslimed out), and a genuine category-scale REE resource in tailings (~217 billion m³ across ~8,500 facilities; >140,000 US abandoned sites). This supports LiT's recovery-headroom thesis *in direction* but validates no specific uplift number. The "16-19% recovery" figure stays an unvalidated assumption; per-impoundment grade/tonnage is flagged **NEEDS EXTERNAL RETRIEVAL**.

**CR-7 — Tailings reprocessing liability/title** (`research/r00-tailings-liability.md`): Surfaced an exposure the documents underweight. Under CERCLA, disturbing a contaminated site can make a party liable for the whole site (10th Cir. held even bare title triggers "owner" liability); under the 1872 Mining Law the US retains title to unpatented claims, so product ownership at orphaned sites isn't automatic. The 2024 Good Samaritan Act opens only a narrow, 15-permit, 7-year pilot whose eligibility test a profit-seeking reprocessor may not cleanly meet. Strategic read: favor **licensing to the operator who already holds the liability and title** over LiT operating orphaned sites itself. Feeds Threats and the Execution risk register.

