**CR-9 — pilot benchmarks** (`research/r00-pilot-benchmarks.md`): Published figures put bench testwork at ~$300-400k and pilot testwork at ~$250k-$1M per program, with a recent 300-500 kg/hr proof-of-concept pilot plant costing ~$2.0M. The finding: LiT's **$700,000 is single-campaign money against a multi-feedstock, two-stage plan**, and the two-stage flowsheet's recirculating streams require continuous (not batch) piloting to prove equilibrium. Month-25 first-license holds only if tied to one lead feedstock.

**CR-10 — adoption/deployment** (`research/r00-adoption-deployment.md`): Two clocks. Reaching a signed agreement at a major operator is **slow** (Jetti: deployed 2019, still only 3 of 23 pipeline projects transitioning to commercial despite BHP/Freeport backing), but post-signature deployment is **fast** (~3 months) when productized into a containerized unit ("Jetti in a Box"). Modular hardware favors LiT's pitch (small footprint, ~9 containers, light civils), but throughput is grinding-limited to ~15 tph/module, so whole-mine scale needs many modules. Both feed the team-capacity Weakness and a fragility flag on Month-25.

